<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>GotCIPA usage trends — private draft for ACTUM</title>
  <style>
    :root {
      --bg: #fafafa;
      --paper: #ffffff;
      --text: #1a1a1a;
      --muted: #555;
      --border: #ddd;
      --banner-bg: #2c2c2c;
      --banner-text: #f5f5f5;
      --accent: #c45c26;
    }
    * { box-sizing: border-box; }
    body {
      margin: 0;
      font-family: Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif;
      background: var(--bg);
      color: var(--text);
      line-height: 1.55;
      font-size: 17px;
    }
    .banner {
      background: var(--banner-bg);
      color: var(--banner-text);
      padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem;
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
      font-size: 0.875rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    }
    .wrap {
      max-width: 720px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 2rem 1.25rem 4rem;
      background: var(--paper);
      border-left: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-right: 1px solid var(--border);
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: 1.75rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      line-height: 1.25;
      margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    }
    .subtitle {
      color: var(--muted);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
    }
    h2 {
      font-size: 1.25rem;
      margin: 2.25rem 0 0.75rem;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
      padding-bottom: 0.35rem;
    }
    h3 { font-size: 1.05rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 0.5rem; }
    p { margin: 0.75rem 0; }
    ul { margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem; padding-left: 1.25rem; }
    li { margin: 0.35rem 0; }
    .stat-row {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
      gap: 1rem;
      margin: 1.25rem 0;
    }
    @media (max-width: 520px) { .stat-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
    .stat {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      padding: 1rem;
    }
    .stat .num {
      font-size: 1.75rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
      color: var(--accent);
    }
    .stat .lbl {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
    }
    figure {
      margin: 1.5rem 0;
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      padding: 1rem;
    }
    figcaption {
      font-size: 0.8rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
      margin-top: 0.75rem;
    }
    .chart-svg { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
    table {
      width: 100%;
      border-collapse: collapse;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
    }
    th, td {
      text-align: left;
      padding: 0.5rem 0.6rem;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    }
    th { font-weight: 600; }
    .callout {
      background: #f4f4f4;
      border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
      padding: 0.85rem 1rem;
      margin: 1rem 0;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }
    .caveats { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--muted); }
    .collab li { list-style: square; }
    footer {
      margin-top: 3rem;
      padding-top: 1rem;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
      font-size: 0.8rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="banner">Private draft for Liz / ACTUM — not for publication. Generated {{ meta.reference_end }}.</div>
  <article class="wrap">
    <h1>GotCIPA audit activity: what the usage data shows</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Aggregate trends from gotcipa.com to support the stop CIPA shakedowns narrative — heroes and victims among small businesses, nonprofits, and public agencies.</p>

    <h2>Why this exists</h2>
    <p>
      GotCIPA (Papaya’s public CIPA risk audit) gives people a way to see whether everyday website tracking may create legal exposure under California’s Invasion of Privacy Act.
      When demand letters and filings accelerate—as your coalition has described—more merchants, agencies, and operators run checks before the legislative window closes.
    </p>
    <p>
      This draft summarizes <strong>aggregate</strong> activity from email-captured leads and completed audit runs. It is meant to complement ACTUM’s policy story: real constituents checking real sites, not a technical treatise on cookies or pixels.
    </p>
    <p class="callout">
      ACTUM has cited a review of 64 CIPA class actions in which average attorney fees were about $2&nbsp;million and average class member recovery about $17. That figure is ACTUM’s; it is included here only as narrative context, not derived from GotCIPA data.
    </p>

    <h2>The spike</h2>
    <p>
      In the most recent 14 days ending {{ meta.reference_end }}, GotCIPA recorded
      <strong>{{ spike.requests_last_14d }}</strong> audit runs across
      <strong>{{ spike.unique_domains_last_14d }}</strong> unique domains, compared with
      {{ spike.requests_prior_14d }} runs and {{ spike.unique_domains_prior_14d }} unique domains in the prior 14 days.
      Email lead captures (excluding internal/test addresses) were
      {{ spike.leads_last_14d }} vs {{ spike.leads_prior_14d }} in those same windows.
    </p>
    <div class="stat-row">
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="num">{{ volume.total_audit_requests }}</div>
        <div class="lbl">Total audit runs (all time in export)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="num">{{ volume.unique_domains_audited }}</div>
        <div class="lbl">Unique domains audited</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="num">{{ volume.unique_emails_users }}</div>
        <div class="lbl">Unique visitor emails (excl. internal/test)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="num">{{ volume.full_accept_gpc_sessions }}</div>
        <div class="lbl">Runs with full accept + GPC session paths</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <figure>
      {{ chart_weekly_requests | safe }}
      <figcaption>Source: audit_requests.csv · weekly audit runs and unique domains · through {{ meta.reference_end }}</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      {{ chart_weekly_leads | safe }}
      <figcaption>Source: audit_leads.csv · weekly email lead captures · through {{ meta.reference_end }}</figcaption>
    </figure>

    {% if volume.repeat_testers_5plus %}
    <h3>Volume hygiene: repeat testers</h3>
    <p>Raw run counts can be inflated when one organization tests repeatedly. Domains with five or more runs in this export:</p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Domain (aggregate only)</th><th>Runs</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {% for row in volume.repeat_testers_5plus[:8] %}
        <tr><td>{{ row.domain }}</td><td>{{ row.count }}</td></tr>
        {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    {% endif %}

    <h2>Who is checking</h2>
    <p>
      Among {{ volume.user_lead_rows }} lead rows (after filtering {{ volume.leads_filtered_internal_test }} internal, test, or disposable addresses),
      about {{ pct_free_email }}% used consumer email domains (Gmail, etc.)—a rough signal of individuals and small operators rather than only enterprise security teams.
    </p>
    {% if public_agency_note %}
    <p class="callout">{{ public_agency_note }}</p>
    {% endif %}

    <figure>
      {{ chart_org_type | safe }}
      <figcaption>Inferred org type · unique audited domains · keyword/TLD heuristics</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      {{ chart_size_proxy | safe }}
      <figcaption>Inferred size proxy · unique audited domains · not firmographic census data</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>What kinds of sites</h2>
    <p>Sector tags are inferred from domain names. Counts below are <strong>unique domains</strong>, not raw audit volume, so one heavy tester does not dominate the story.</p>
    <figure>
      {{ chart_sectors | safe }}
      <figcaption>Top sectors · unique domains · inferred from URL keywords</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>Category-level examples (no contact details)</h3>
    <ul>
      {% for ex in anonymized_examples %}
      <li>{{ ex }}</li>
      {% endfor %}
    </ul>

    <h2>Middle tech and ordinary commerce</h2>
    <p>
      Most audited properties in this export look like everyday commerce and services—restaurants and suppliers, regional healthcare and veterinary groups, retailers, and similar—not a roster of large consumer platforms alone.
      Sites in this position often use mainstream analytics and advertising tags for ordinary business reasons; GotCIPA is built to help defense-side teams and operators understand exposure, not to fuel offensive targeting.
    </p>
    <p>
      This export does <strong>not</strong> include a per-run inventory of Meta pixels, Google tags, or other vendors. A future CSV column (e.g. <code>tracker_vendors</code>) can slot into the same regeneration pipeline when available.
    </p>

    <h2>What we cannot claim from this dataset</h2>
    <ul class="caveats">
      <li><strong>No geography or IP:</strong> GotCIPA does not store visitor IP or geo; we cannot chart “uptick from Texas” or similar from these files.</li>
      <li><strong>Size and sector are inferred</strong>, not verified firmographics.</li>
      <li><strong>Verdict fields are sparse</strong> in the leads export ({% if methodology.verdict_sparse %}most rows lack a filled verdict{% else %}verdict coverage is limited{% endif %}).</li>
      <li><strong>No individual emails or identifiable contacts</strong> appear in this document by design.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Questions for Liz — collaboration</h2>
    <ul class="collab">
      <li>Does the 14-day vs prior-14-day spike framing match what you are seeing in filing and demand-letter velocity?</li>
      <li>Which sections are useful for elected-official meetings vs coalition email—what should we cut or expand?</li>
      <li>Are category-level examples enough, or do you want a short list of named domains approved for closed-door use only?</li>
      <li>When you share the advocacy email template, should Papaya send to the {{ volume.unique_emails_users }} filtered user emails as a separate mobilization step?</li>
      <li>Any additional aggregate cuts (e.g. nonprofit-only) you want in the next CSV refresh?</li>
    </ul>

    <footer>
      Papaya · GotCIPA data story pipeline · Replace <code>data/audit_leads.csv</code> and <code>data/audit_requests.csv</code>, then run <code>python scripts/build_story.py</code>.
    </footer>
  </article>
</body>
</html>
